example.code:
using ( webView.DeferInput() )
{
    // Perform operations with all input blocked.
} // Restores input processing to its previous status.

// Block mouse and touch input.
using ( webView.DeferInput( ViewInput.Mouse | ViewInput.Touch ) )
{
    // Perform operations with mouse and touch input blocked.
    
    using ( webView.DeferInput( ViewInput.Keyboard ) )
    {
        // Perform operations with mouse, touch and keyboard input blocked.
        
    } // Restores input processing to its previous status, blocking only
      // mouse and touch input.
      
} // Restores input processing to its initial status.

member.example:
An example of usage:

webView.CreateObject("MyObject");
webView.SetObjectProperty("MyObject", "color", "blue");

You can now access this object's property via Javascript on any 
page loaded into this WebView:

var myColor = MyObject.color; // value would be "blue"

An example of usage:

public void OnSelectItem(object sender, JSCallbackEventArgs e)
{
    System.Console.WriteLine( "Player selected item: " + e.args[0].ToString() );
}

public void initWebView()
{
    webView.CreateObject("MyObject");
    webView.SetObjectCallback("MyObject", "SelectItem", OnSelectItem);
}

You can now call the function OnSelectItem from Javascript:

MyObject.SelectItem("shotgun");

            Example of Usage:
            
            [STAThread]
            static void Main( string[] args )
            {
                // Check if our executable is running as a child process.
                if ( WebCore.IsChildProcess )
                {
                    // Pass control over to Awesomium. This call will return
                    // when we are done with using this child process.
                    WebCore.ChildProcessMain();
                    // Exit this child process.
                    return;
                }
            
                // Continue normal execution.
                Application.EnableVisualStyles();
                Application.SetCompatibleTextRenderingDefault( false );
            
                // You can specify WebCoreConfig.CHILD_PROCESS_SELF ("self"),
                // as a shortcut to the path of this executable.
                // This initialization can also take place in the constructor of your
                // main form (Form1 in this scenario), right before the InitializeComponent call.
                WebCore.Initialize( new WebCoreConfig() { ChildProcessPath = WebCoreConfig.CHILD_PROCESS_SELF } );
            
                Application.Run( new Form1() );
            }
            


            You can also use this in a WPF application, but you need to follow some steps
            that will let you define your own entry point:
            


            In Solution Explorer, select App.xaml (Application.xaml in VB)
            and then in Properties window, change the Build Action from 
            ApplicationDefinition to Page.
            


            Add your custom entry point to App.xaml.cs (Application.xaml.vb in VB).
            
            
            Here is an example:
            
            [STAThread()]
            static void Main( string[] args )
            {
                // Check if our executable is running as a child process.
                if ( WebCore.IsChildProcess )
                {
                    // Pass control over to Awesomium. This call will return
                    // when we are done with using this child process.
                    WebCore.ChildProcessMain();
                    // Exit this child process.
                    return;
                }
                
                // Continue normal execution.
                App app = new App();
                
                // You can specify WebCoreConfig.CHILD_PROCESS_SELF ("self"),
                // as a shortcut to the path of this executable.
                // This initialization can also take place in the constructor of your
                // main window, right before the InitializeComponent call.
                WebCore.Initialize( new WebCoreConfig() { ChildProcessPath = WebCoreConfig.CHILD_PROCESS_SELF } );
                
                app.InitializeComponent();
                app.Run();
            }

The list is set using a comma-separated string of URLs. For example, you can specify:
config.AuthServerWhitelist = "*example.com,*foobar.com,*baz";
which would tell Awesomium that any URL ending in either 'example.com', 'foobar.com' or 'baz' is in the permitted list. Without the '*' prefix, the URL has to match exactly.

